The presentation, titled "What healthcare leaders need to know: Preparing for the COVID-19" happened February 26, with representatives from the National Ebola Training and Education Center. 
As part of the presentation to hospitals, Dr. James Lawler, a professor at the University of Nebraska Medical Center gave his "best guess" estimates of how much the virus might spread in the US.
Lawler's estimates include:
4.8 million hospitalizations associated with the novel coronavirus
96 million cases overall in the US
480,000 deaths
Overall, the slide points out that hospitals should prepare for an impact to the system that's 10 times a severe flu season. ï¿¼AHA webinar

"The AHA regularly hosts webinars and conference calls that include a variety of voices and opinions that seek to provide relevant information to professionals at hospitals and health systems that are on the front lines of preparing for and protecting their patients and communities," a spokeswoman for the AHA told Business Insider in an emailed statement. author: abcnews
comment:
The Emmett Till Anti-lynching Act, a bill to make lynching a hate crime under federal law, passed the House on Wednesday, making it the first attempt since 1900 poised to successfully make its way through Congress.
-
The vote was 410-4.
-
The legislation is named for Emmett Till, a 14-year-old African American boy who was kidnapped, beaten and lynched in 1955 after he was accused of whistling at a white woman.
Rep. Bobby Rush, who introduced the bill in January 2019, said it will finally outlaw "an American evil."
-
Lynchings were used in the U.S., predominantly in the South, from the 1880s to 1960s to terrorize black Americans. From 1882-1968, 4,743 lynchings occurred in the U.S., with 3,446 involving victims who were black, according to the NAACP.
-
Rush said the bill is expected to pass the Senate by the end of the week, before the end of Black History Month, and then makes its way to the Oval Office.
-
Asked if they believed Trump would sign the bill, Rep. Karen Bass said, "How could he not?"

author: abcnews
comment:
Nikita Pearl Waligwa, who starred in the 2016 Disney film "Queen of Katwe," has died from a brain tumor at the age of 15, according to her school in Uganda.
-
Waligwa had been attending Gayaza High School in Kampala while she had cancer. The school tweeted a heartfelt announcement on her passing late Saturday night.
-
"You were a darling to many and we have lost you to [a] brain tumor at such a tender age," the school tweeted. "Rest in Perfect Peace dear."
-
Waligwa starred in the 2016 Disney film "Queen of Katwe," a biographical film about Ugandan chess player Phiona Mutesi, who came from the slums to be one of the top players in the world. Waligwa played Gloria, Mutesi's friend and fellow chess player who says in chess, "the small one can become the big one."
-
The movie was a hit among Ugandan audiences who saw local actors on the same screen as Hollywood stars like Lupita Nyong'o and David Oyelowo.
-
Oyelowo shared his condolences on Instagram: "She was a ball of light in @queenofkatwemovie and in life. Her battle with a brain tumor was humbling to witness. Her light will live on."
-
(Disney is the parent company of ABC News.)
